ially like the god alignment system. Dialog options don't influence the plot but they do influence gameplay because your dialog choices are aligned with one of four deities (Athena, Apollo, Ares and Hermes). Winning their favour by choosing their dialogs or dedicating your deeds (ingame achievements) to them lets you level up in their respective skill trees and unlock different powers and buffs. To me it feels very satisfying to devote yourself to a god (Athena rules and anyone who disagrees will eat my spear), it really gets me immersed.\n\nThe dialogs and characters are mostly well written. Each of your companions have different personalities, and they interact between them and with the enviroment in different ways (Pan is snarky and will go on about old legends and trivia, Achilles is obnoxious and will brag about being the best fighter ever, and so on). Like Mass Effect, you take your ship (the Argo, a steampunk-ish mechanical Greek galley) to different locations and decide which companions will go ashore with you. Of course it's much more limited and samll than Mass Effect, with only five or six main locations or so, and only four companions to choose from, although you collect a few other characters with whom you can speak while on board the Argo.\n\nThe combat, although not very tricky, is fluid, fun and bloody, and can get quite spectacular once you start throwing god powers all over the place.\n\nAesthetically, it's good enough. Some of the enviroments look pretty and colorful, like Iolcus palace (I really liked the guards openning the doors for you, I know it's probably there just to hide a loading time but it made me feel like a king and I've seen too many magical self-openning doors in games to appreciate the detail), while others are much more dull and uninspired. The bronze in your armour is shiny and many of the armours and wepons themselves are not too overly fantastical in design, which I like.\n\nI haven't experienced crashes or major bugs that I remember, as many reviews say, and I played for several hours at a time. I guess I got lucky. I bough this game on a sale for dirt cheap (1.75 EUR) fearing that it would be awful or crash on me, but I was pleasantly surprised and, after completing it, I woudn't mind having paid more for it."}, {"votes_down": 3, "written_during_early_access": false, "voted_up": true, "language": "english", "timestamp_created": 1422271473, "weighted_vote_score": "0.498357", "steam_purchase": true, "votes_funny": 0, "recommendationid": "14176345", "votes_up": 4, "comment_count": 0, "author": {"steamid": "76561198080772755", "num_reviews": 15, "last_played": 1436009421, "num_games_owned": 432, "playtime_last_two_weeks": 0, "playtime_forever": 2264}, "timestamp_updated": 1422596205, "received_for_free": false, "review": "I really enjoyed its unique leveling up system which is still very good even to this day standards and a retaelling of a greek story worthy of being told now admittly no new game + were you can keep you old abitly while leveling up new would be nice but when it comes down to it how many games let you be a greek king kicking ass form your dead wife's grave to hell and back again\n\nEdit \n\nI just complete the game on the hardest diffculty and have to say even though this game has a great leveling up system and bosses that are design with attack patterns instead of over powered attacks with high health bars and no instanted death and even though limit a varied range of wepoins and armour \n\nI will emit the game has some downsides like for some reason the carmea is some annnoying and theres never a map but to be fair it not like you get lost all the areas are small which kinda suck as well and alt tab some crases the game.\n\nNever the less after passing this game on the hardes diffculty a would give it a 8/10 and recommend it to many people"}, {"votes_down": 4, "written_during_early_access": false, "voted_up": true, "language": "english", "timestamp_created": 1468740611, 